        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/22688",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Just use the STANDARD definition\n\nZend_Measure_Length::STANDARD resolves to meter as meter is the default length definition world wide.\nZend_Measure_Force::STANDARD resolves to newton... and so on.\n\nThis feature is available since the class has arrived incubator.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-06-30T06:12:12.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-06-30T06:12:12.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/22690",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mben",
                        "name": "mben",
                        "displayName": "Marc Bennewitz (GIATA mbH)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Hi Thomas\n\nI don't mean the already implemented  \"STANDARD\" type because the \"STANDARD\" type is only the default type for a specific measure.\nOn my example above the \"STANDARD\" type would be display \"1000 m\" but not \"1 km\".\n\nOn my project I like to display a short value for a time measure. This is a other example to to this issue:\n( Zend_Measure_Time is from ZF-3536 )\n{code}\n\/\/ e.g $row->durationMs == 5400000 == 1,5h \n$videoDuration = new Zend_Measure_Time($row->durationMs, Zend_Measure_Time::MILLISECOND);\necho $videoDuration->convertTo(Zend_Measure_Time::STANDARD, 2);  \/\/ display \"90 min\"\necho $videoDuration->convertTo(Zend_Measure_Time::AUTO, 2);  \/\/ This can display \"1.5 h\"\n\/\/ -> next row\n\/\/ e.g $row->durationMs == 34534\n$videoDuration = new Zend_Measure_Time($row->durationMs, Zend_Measure_Time::MILLISECOND);\necho $videoDuration->convertTo(Zend_Measure_Time::STANDARD, 2);  \/\/ display \"0.78 min\"\necho $videoDuration->convertTo(Zend_Measure_Time::AUTO, 2);  \/\/ This can display \"34.53 s\"\n{code}\nThe \"AUTO\" type can create the shortest way to display the value by the given precision.\n\nIn some measures more type groups are available\ne.g. Zend_Measure_Length\n  - based on meters\n  - based on miles\nThan it can handled by more \"AUTO\" types like Zend_Measure_Length::METER_AUTO and Zend_Measure_Length::MILE_AUTO.\nA only selected \"AUTO\" type can use the defined \"[GROUP]_AUTO\" type for the \"STANDARD\" type. -> On Zend_Measure_Length it would be Zend_Measure_Length::METER_AUTO.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mben",
                        "name": "mben",
                        "displayName": "Marc Bennewitz (GIATA mbH)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-06-30T07:12:27.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-06-30T07:12:27.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/22691",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "This is not possible.\n\nSeveral measurements can not be automatically converted between same types because they will then miss informations or be converted to a false scale.\n\nSee Length for example:\nInch... which to convert to ??\nFeet_Us, Feet_French, Feet_Italian, Feet_Survey ???\n\nThere is no practicable way to have such a grouping implemented.\nBut you can do this yourself, if you know which conversion units you want to convert to...\nThere is a getValue, and a getType method.... a simple switch statement and you can decide which unit to convert to.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-06-30T07:45:25.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-06-30T07:45:25.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/22694",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mben",
                        "name": "mben",
                        "displayName": "Marc Bennewitz (GIATA mbH)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "mh ok - This I have not thought. But very thanks for your donated time.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mben",
                        "name": "mben",
                        "displayName": "Marc Bennewitz (GIATA mbH)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-06-30T08:11:52.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-06-30T08:11:52.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/32184",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Closed as \"won't fix\" after reviewing it once again.\n\nIt's not possible to use one fixed scale like Meter-> Kilometer and so on... many scales use multiple subscales like mentioned in past not only for length but also for other measurements.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-06-25T08:39:00.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-06-25T08:39:00.000+0000"
                }
            ]
        }
